{"source_key":"sha256-784c2f10bfe4a26d66c37ad545f72f01","record_index":24848,"record_hash":"sha256:165aa7d6a8a0925cf81729f6469c6dec106fe393374cbb53483cd8dfaa706cac","timestamp":"2026-05-11T09:34:31.606Z","kind":"message","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:message","role":"assistant","text":"Yes, theoretically this improves the hot path quite a lot.\n\nBefore, every capture did:\n\n```text\nread full :transcript list\nparse every transcript JSON envelope\nextract record_hash\ndedupe new records\nwrite full :transcript list back\n```\n\nFor your one imported session, that meant reading/parsing roughly:\n\n```text\n~49MB transcript list\n24,216 JSON envelopes\n```\n\njust to answer “which hashes have I already seen?”\n\nNow every capture does:\n\n```text\nread :record-hashes set\ndedupe new records\nappend only new :transcript entries\nadd only new hashes to :record-hashes\n```\n\nFor the same session, the dedupe read is roughly:\n\n```text\n24,216 hashes * ~71 bytes each ≈ 1.6-1.8MB raw hash strings\n```\n\nplus JSON/set overhead. That’s still not free, but it’s a very different scale from parsing 49MB of transcript envelopes, especially because the old envelopes include large tool output/source records.\n\nThe write side is the bigger win:\n\n```text\nold: write whole transcript list again\nnew: append only new transcript entries\n```\n\nSo if a hook runs after one new record is added, we now write one transcript entry plus one hash, not a 50MB list replacement. GitMeta’s log also records the appended entries and added hashes rather than another full transcript-list snapshot.\n\nSo: yes, for the “same session keeps growing” lifecycle-hook pattern, this is the right direction. We should still measure once you reset/import again, but the complexity class changed from “work proportional to entire stored transcript bytes” to “work proportional to hash index plus new records.”","tool_name":null,"tool_input":null,"source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-05-11T09:34:31.606Z